  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying guide</h2>

      <h3>Go vs Original for hiking</h3>
      <p>
        This is the real choice. The <strong>AeroPress Go</strong> is better for most hikers because it is tidy and self-contained. The <strong>AeroPress Original</strong> is better for ultralight hikers because it weighs less and gives you more freedom to build your own kit.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you mostly do day hikes, road trips, hut stays, or easy overnights, buy the Go and move on. If you are trimming gear hard for multi-day backpacking, the Original makes more sense.
      </p>

      <h3>Paper vs metal filters on the trail</h3>
      <p>
        Paper filters are the easiest answer outdoors. They make a cleaner cup, need less water to clean up, and are almost weightless. Metal filters make a cup with more body, but they also ask for more rinsing and a little more care. If you want more detail, our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-brewing-method.html">best AeroPress brewing method guide</a> and <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-brew-time.html">best AeroPress brew time guide</a> help you dial in the cup side of that decision.
      </p>

      <h3>Grinder and scale trade-offs</h3>
      <p>
        A grinder gives you fresher coffee. A scale gives you repeatability. Both add weight. For most hikers, I would choose <strong>one</strong> of those, not both. On longer trips, a manual grinder earns its spot more easily. On short trips, pre-ground coffee and a simple recipe usually make more sense. If ratios are the part you always second-guess, read our <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a> next.
      </p>

      <h3>When a hiking upgrade is actually worth it</h3>
      <p>
        Buy an upgrade only if it fixes something real. The Flow Control cap is worth it if drip-through annoys you. The Prismo is worth it if you want a richer cup and do not mind rinsing a metal filter. Extra gear that solves no problem is just backpack clutter with better branding.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you already own the Go, our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-go-recipe.html">best AeroPress Go recipe</a> guide is the most useful next read. Better recipe first. More gear second.
      </p>
    </BuyingGuideSection>
